<sec id="id-9bdb13cd-484c-4d1a-b1d8-10e4e1d17ed1"><title><bold><?fontoxml-change-deletion author-id="5191008" change-id="c8af0c20-937a-4f5e-fb5f-4bcc6601fc49" text="Box 7 - " timestamp="1667321878488"?><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="8848353" change-id="3649fcdc-6a24-481d-e925-7d6d194f80bf" timestamp="1666182562990"?>Women-only job openings in organizations<?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="3649fcdc-6a24-481d-e925-7d6d194f80bf"?></bold></title><?fontoxml-change-deletion author-id="8848353" change-id="9bce9a05-5dce-48c6-c5bf-6e8733276d46" text="Box 7 - Women-only job openings in organizations" timestamp="1666182561568"?><?fontoxml-change-deletion author-id="9276395" change-id="a6429a09-9957-4fb2-fa97-2854dab2c2c7" text="[Former Box 7 ]" timestamp="1675426740732"?><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="8848353" change-id="3d5bd909-e214-48a8-92b3-8e2093a6ddb8" timestamp="1666182556219"?><p>Companies whose workforce is predominantly male, often because they involve activities usually linked to men, such as engineering and technology companies, have reserved a percentage of vacancies for women, as a way of guaranteeing that part of their workforce is occupied by women. For example, an organization aimed or targeted 50% of its vacancies for the Trainee Program for women, after its recruitment team noticed that most of these vacancies were occupied by men.<?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="3d5bd909-e214-48a8-92b3-8e2093a6ddb8"?></p><p/></sec>